[Black "Chapter 2 Scheveningen Formation"]

{In Chapters 2 and 3, Black establishes the modest e6/d6 central pawn duo that resembles the Scheveningen structure, one of Black's most solid and flexible defensive systems in the Open Sicilian. White adopts the typical scheme: Qe2, Rd1 and Rac1.}

1. e4 c5 2. d4 cxd4 3. c3 dxc3 4. Nxc3 Nc6 5. Nf3 d6 6. Bc4 e6 {[%entry]} 7. O-O Be7 8. Qe2 Nf6 9. Rd1 e5 (9... Bd7 10. Nb5 (10. Bf4 e5) 10... Qb8 11. Bf4 Ne5 12. Nxd6+ Bxd6 13. Rxd6 Qxd6 14. Nxe5) (9... O-O? 10. e5 Ne8 11. exd6 Bxd6 (11... Nxd6 12. Bf4) 12. Nb5 Qe7 13. Bg5 f6 14. Be3) 10. Be3 O-O 11. Rac1 Be6 (11... Bg4 12. h3 Bh5 13. g4 Bg6 14. Nh4 Rc8 15. Nf5) (11... Bd7 12. a3 a6 13. b4) (11... Ng4 12. Bc5) 12. b4 a6 (12... Nxb4 13. Nxe5) 13. a3 Rc8 14. Bxe6 fxe6 15. Qa2 *
